  <brief_summary>
    <textblock>
      Diabetes mellitus in children and adolescents is a source of stress and poor quality of life
      for themselves and their family. Development of adaptive coping strategies may be improved by
      focused parent and children training. This study assesses a cognitive behavioral treatment
      (CBT) for children/adolescents with diabetes and their parents in comparison with standard
      health educational interventions. The investigators main aim is to verify that the CBT
      program improves overall balance of glycaemia better than phone contact without CBT content
      (control group). Secondary objectives are expected improvements of health-related quality of
      life and coping styles in parents and children.
    </textblock>
  </brief_summary>
